Because S must first expand as  

S → NT26 NT14  

and NT14 has only the rule  

NT14 → 't2',  

the very last symbol of any sentence generated by the grammar must be the terminal t2.  
The given string ends with t11, not t2, so it cannot be produced by the grammar.

No

The start production is  

S → NT26 NT14

In any derivation NT14’s yield must appear after the yield of NT26, i.e. it must be the last part of the generated string.  
NT14 has only one production that contains a terminal symbol:

NT14 → 't2'

Therefore every string in the language must end with the single terminal t2.

The given string ends with t1, not t2, so it cannot be produced by S.

Hence the grammar does not generate the provided string.

No
